{{Infobox criminal | name = Ashanta Baghphukan | image_name = | image_size =200px | image_alt = | image_caption = | birth_name = Tarun Phukan | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1963|03|31}} | birth_place = [[Assam]] | death_date = | death_place = | cause = | alias = | motive = | charge = Terrorism | conviction = | conviction_penalty = | conviction_status = Missing | occupation = | spouse = Hangshipa Hazarika alias Malina Ingtipi alias Hema Hansipi | parents = | children = Kareng (son) }}
'''Ashanta Baghphukan''' ([[Assamese language|Assamese]]: '''অশান্ত বাঘফুকন''') (born: 1963), real name '''Tarun Phukan''', is the Chief Organising Secretary of [[ULFA]], the banned terrorist group of [[Assam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://assampolice.com/departments/cid/lookout/wanted_golap.htm|title=Most Wanted|publisher=Assam Police|accessdate=13 December 2009}}</ref> He, along with five other senior ULFA leaders, went missing during the Operation All Clear carried out against the group by Royal Bhutanese Army in December, 2003.<ref name="ab">{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2007/20070403/nation.htm#13|title=ULFA ‘tries’ to build rights violation case against government|last=Bora|first=Bijay Sankar|date=April 2, 2007|publisher=The Tribune|accessdate=13 December 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091028125615/http://www.tribuneindia.com/2007/20070403/nation.htm| archivedate= 28 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>
==Handing over the kins== On December 24, 2003, Phukan's wife Hangshipa Hazarika (alias Malina Ingtipi alias Hema Hansipi<ref name="ab" />) who is also a member of the group's women wing, and son Kareng were handed over to the [[District Collector|Deputy Commissioner]] of [[Nalbari]] by the Bhutanese Royal Government. They were accompanied by 64 kins of other militants of the group. The Nalbari district administration later took them to the Tamulpur 30-bedded hospital campus for primary check-ups.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oldcontent.northeastunlimited.com/2965.html|title=Bhutan hands over 64 ultra kin|last=Kalita|first=Ramen|date=Dec 25, 2003|publisher=The Assam Tribune|accessdate=13 December 2009}}</ref>
==Kin’s fast-unto-death== On March 24, 2003 the wives of the missing leaders has started a fast-unto-death demanding information on the whereabouts of their husbands.<ref name="ab" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saag.org/common/uploaded_files/paper2241.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614083458/http://www.saag.org/common/uploaded_files/paper2241.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=June 14, 2011 |title=Assam: Army Intensifies Operations Against ULFA |last=Kumar |first=Dr Ananda |date=May 10, 2007 |publisher=SAAG |accessdate=13 December 2009 }}</ref> They had been admitted to [[Gauhati Medical College and Hospital|Guwahati Medical College Hospital]] and were being nasal fed for they had refused to take food in custody.<ref name="ab" />
== Interference of court== On March 13, 2007, the [[Guwahati High Court]] directed the [[Government of India|Central]] as well as the [[Government of Assam|State Government]] to submit information about the missing leaders on March 30 of the year. The central government accordingly submitted to the court an instruction related to it. The court, however, after proper examining the instruction, asked both governments to file an affidavit within seven days.<ref name="ab" />
