{{For|the other Ottoman general Şevket Pasha|Shevket Turgut Pasha}} {{Ottoman Turkish name|Mahmud Shevket|Pasha}} {{Infobox Officeholder | honorific-prefix = | name = Mahmud Shevket | honorific-suffix = [[Pasha]] | image = Mahmut sevket.jpg | image_size = 235px | caption = | office1 = [[Grand Vizier of the Ottoman Empire]] | monarch1 = [[Mehmed V]] | term_start1 = 23 January 1913 | term_end1 = 11 June 1913 | predecessor1 = [[Kâmil Pasha]] | successor1 = [[Said Halim Pasha]] | birth_date = 1856 | birth_place = [[Baghdad]], [[Baghdad Eyalet]], [[Ottoman Empire]] | death_date = 11 June 1913 | death_place = [[Istanbul]], [[Ottoman Empire]] | blank1 = | data1 = | party = | spouse = | relations = | children = | residence = | alma_mater = | allegiance = {{flag|Ottoman Empire}} | branch = {{army|Ottoman Empire}} | serviceyears = | rank = General | battles = | occupation = | profession = | religion = | signature = | footnotes = }}
'''Mahmud Shevket Pasha''' ({{lang-tr|Mahmut Şevket Paşa}}; 1856 – 11 June 1913)<ref name="DKF">David Kenneth Fieldhouse: ''Western imperialism in the Middle East 1914-1958''. Oxford University Press, 2006 p.17</ref> was an [[Ottoman Turks|Ottoman]] [[general]] and [[Diplomat|statesman]], known for his active role in establishing a [[military aviation]] program. He was [[Grand vizier|prime minister]] of the [[Ottoman Empire]] from 23 January 1913 until his death by assassination.
== Early life and career == He was born in [[Baghdad]], where he finished his primary education before going on to the Military Academy ({{lang-tr|Mekteb-i Harbiye}}) in [[Constantinople]].<ref>Finkel, Caroline, ''Osman's Dream'', (Basic Books, 2005), 57; ''Istanbul was only adopted as the city's official name in 1930..''.</ref> He joined the army in 1882 as a lieutenant. He spent some time in France investigating military technology and was stationed in [[Crete]] for a while. He then returned to the Military Academy as a faculty member.
He worked under [[Colmar Freiherr von der Goltz]] (Goltz Pasha) for a while and traveled to Germany. He was then appointed as governor of the [[Kosovo Vilayet]], where he commanded the 3rd Army, which was later known as ''Hareket Ordusu'' ("Army of Action") after its involvement in suppressing the [[counter-revolutionary]] absolutist reactionaries in the [[31 March Incident]]. A voice recording of Mahmud Shevket Pasha speaking to rally his troops against the counter-revolutionaries in 1909 was released in by journalist [[Murat Bardakçı]] in 2012.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xIRUC8p0t7M</ref>
He played an important role in ending the 31 March Incident and with it, the reign of [[Abdul Hamid II]]. He served as [[Grand Vizier]] to [[Mehmed V]] from 23 January 1913.<ref>{{Cite book|author=Feroz Ahmad |year=2014 |title=Turkey: The Quest for Identity |edition=second |location=London |publisher=Oneworld |page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hMRpAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT44 44] |isbn=978-1-78074-301-1}}</ref> He was assassinated in Constantinople, on 11 June 1913 in a revenge attack by a relative of the murdered [[Nazım Pasha]].<ref name="DKF"/>
Among other things, he is credited with the creation of the [[Ottoman Air Force]] in 1911 and bringing the first automobile to Constantinople. Mahmud Shevket Pasha gave much importance to a military aviation program and as a result the [[Ottoman Air Force]] became one of the pioneering aviation institutions in the world.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hvkk.tsk.tr/EN/IcerikDetay.aspx?ID=19 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-11-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007104345/http://www.hvkk.tsk.tr/EN/IcerikDetay.aspx?ID=19 |archivedate=7 October 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>
Though raised as a Turk, various sources claim that he may have also had [[Iraqi people|Iraqi Arab]],<ref>Ali Bilgenoğlu, ''Osmanlı Devleti'nde Arap milliyetçi cemiyetler'', Müdafaa-i Hukuk Yayınları, 2007, p. 87.]</ref> [[Georgia (country)|Georgian]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1909/05/17/101881418.pdf |title=New York Times, May 17, 1909 | work=The New York Times | date=17 May 1909}}</ref> [[Chechens|Chechen]],<ref name="Erkan101">İsmail Hâmi Danişmend, ''Osmanlı Devlet Erkânı'', Türkiye Yayınevi, İstanbul, 1971, p. 101. {{Tr icon}}</ref> or [[Circassians|Circassian]]<ref>Nâzım Tektaş, ''Sadrazamlar: Osmanlı'da ikinci adam saltanatı'', Çatı Kitapları, 2002, p. .</ref> ancestry.
<gallery> File:Mahmut Schevket Pascha.jpg|Mahmud Shevket Pasha by Simon Agopian. (1857−1921) File:MAHMUTSEVKEtPASA.jpg|Mahmud Shevket Pasha is often considered to be the founding father of the [[Turkish Air Force]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.incirlik.af.mil/news/story.asp?storyID=123032165 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-09-05 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304031410/http://www.incirlik.af.mil/news/story.asp?storyID=123032165 |archivedate=4 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> File:Mahmut1.jpg|The pistols carried by Mahmud Shevket Pasha's assassins. File:Automobile blindé & Etat major de Chefket Pacha.jpg|The first automobile in Constantinople. </gallery>
